{:itonami.blueprint/id "cloud-itonami-3020"
 :itonami.blueprint/name "Community Railway Rolling Stock Manufacturing"
 :itonami.blueprint/isic-rev5 "3020"
 :itonami.blueprint/domain :manufacturing/railway-rolling-stock
 :itonami.blueprint/license "AGPL-3.0-or-later"
 :itonami.blueprint/social-impact [:rail-safety :supply-resilience :decarbonization]
 :itonami.blueprint/governor :rolling-stock-manufacturing-governor
 :itonami.blueprint/robotics true
 :itonami.blueprint/required-technologies [:robotics :identity :forms :dmn :bpmn :audit-ledger :eda :cae]
 :itonami.blueprint/optional-technologies []
 :itonami.blueprint/status :public-oss
 :itonami.blueprint/maturity :implemented
 :itonami.blueprint/implemented-slice
 "RollingStockAdvisor ⊣ Rolling Stock Manufacturing Governor,
 langgraph-clj StateGraph (langgraph.graph,
 rolling-stock.operation/build), append-only audit ledger
 (rolling-stock.store/ledger + append-ledger!, mem-store). Fixes a prior
 gap: `rolling-stock.sim` hand-wired the advisor's four proposal
 functions straight into `governor/evaluate` and printed the verdict to
 stdout -- no `operation.cljc`, no `langgraph.graph` state-graph/
 add-node/compile-graph call anywhere in `src/`, and no append-only
 ledger on the store at all -- despite `deps.edn` correctly declaring
 real `io.github.com-junkawasaki/langgraph-clj` (with a real `:git/sha`)
 at the top level. Now: a genuinely compiled StateGraph (`:intake ->
 :advise -> :govern -> :decide -+-> :commit / :request-approval ->
 :commit / :hold`) with `interrupt-before #{:request-approval}` + an
 in-memory checkpointer for real human-in-the-loop resume, mirroring
 `pastaops.operation` (cloud-itonami-isic-1074) node/edge structure. The
 advisor (`rolling-stock.advisor`) stays PLAIN FUNCTIONS (not a
 `defprotocol` -- wiring it into a real graph node did not require one);
 `advisor/propose` is the new dispatch seam `build`'s `:advisor` opt
 accepts (a plain 1-arg fn of request -> proposal), swappable for a real
 LLM backend or a test double. Four closed-vocabulary ops
 (`:log-production-record` / `:schedule-maintenance` /
 `:flag-safety-defect` / `:request-release-review`), all `:effect
 :propose` only. `:flag-safety-defect` ALWAYS escalates to a human QC
 inspector via the compiled graph's `:request-approval` node
 (checkpoint-based resume) unless a HARD governor violation (e.g. a
 safety-critical defect, or process-control-forbidden language) blocks
 it before the escalate branch is ever reached. Proven end-to-end by
 `test/rolling_stock/operation_graph_test.clj` exercising commit /
 hard-hold (unverified unit; critical-defect hard-block that pre-empts
 what would otherwise be an always-escalate op) / escalate-approve /
 escalate-reject through the REAL compiled graph, including a falsifiable
 proof that a custom injected advisor's own (randomly generated,
 non-hardcoded) proposal `:detail` is what lands in the committed
 ledger fact -- not a graph-internal literal. `rolling-stock.store` now
 also exposes an append-only `:ledger` atom (`ledger`/`append-ledger!`)
 alongside its original `:data` value helpers (unchanged). Observed but
 OUT OF SCOPE for this fix: `rolling-stock.governor`'s
 `release-forbidden-violations` / `process-control-block-violations`
 keyword scans match on bare substrings of the op vocabulary itself
 (e.g. \"release\" inside `:request-release-review`'s own proposal text,
 \"weld\" inside a safety-critical defect's own description) -- this
 makes `:request-release-review` permanently hard-blocked through the
 mock advisor's own wording, and adds a second (redundant but
 non-contradicting) hard violation alongside the intended
 `:safety-defect-escalation` block for critical defects. Governor logic
 was reused unchanged per this fix's scope; this is a pre-existing
 governor characteristic, not introduced here, and is called out for a
 follow-up rather than silently patched."}
